Challenge: Gibberish

echo "filename" | tr -cd '[:alnum:]._-'

Sanitizes the string "filename" by removing any characters that are not alphanumeric (a-z, A-Z, 0-9), a dot (.), an underscore (_), or a hyphen (-). The result is a clean string containing only the allowed characters.


Use Cases

Sanitizing Filenames: This command is commonly used to remove unwanted or problematic characters from filenames, ensuring compatibility across different filesystems.

Preparing Data for URLs: It can also be useful for cleaning strings that will be used in URLs by removing spaces and special characters.

Security: Helps prevent injection attacks by ensuring that only expected characters are present in user inputs.